      "text": "Ticket\nLock\n(Redis)",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "center",
      "verticalAlign": "middle",
      "containerId": "8ghodm-I1J41x_jaw5xDS",
      "originalText": "Ticket\nLock\n(Redis)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "kDz3DxUbXyKHRvZAK8IYU",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1410.7463521667132,
      "y": 10472.472677317352,
      "width": 2177.99853515625,
      "height": 2340,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bIM",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1591871709,
      "version": 3386,
      "versionNonce": 1612131057,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1770404286338,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How we will get available sheets for an event -> we will first check into database for all avaialbe\nsheets and then for sheets we will check in Redis if reserved we will filter out an sent back to client.\nwe need distributed lock due to booking service need to horizontally scaled so multiple booking\nservice will be there and all of them need this detail. \n\n\nInterview ask -> What happend if this lock goes down?\n\ni -> we would detect that this is down and we would immediately make it up that means if any of user\n    reserve that in last 10 minutes will lost their reservation and so in theory for a 10 minute window\nwe could have several users go to a payment page and try to book the same ticket because this is a postgres\nDB here and we still have the ACID properties on the write to available or booked meaning one write need\nto complete before another one could write\nwhoever end up submitting the purchase first is going to win and the other ones will get error and this is \na bad user experience. this is the conversation that we would have with the product team like is it okay\nif it is okay then that is the disaster when lock goes down.\nThen we will have small 10 minutes window where we are not going to lose our consistency guarantees but user\nare going to have bad user experience\n\n\nDeep Dive\nNon Functional Requirements ->\n\n1 Low Latency Search\n\nHow we handle low latency search -> we know our current solution is slow because we do a full table scan\nCommon solution for search problems like this is to introduce search optimize database and a very popular\none and one that recommended in our interviews is called elasticsearch.\n\nHow ElasticSearch work -> way that elasticsearch works is along with other things it builds an inverted index\n    to make searching documents by terms really quickly so we can imaging we have an event and the event has\nsome text for the name and description and may be other things that describe the event and what we are going\nto do is we are going to tokenize that string or those set of strings and create terms from them so we could\nimagine that the string might be the Philadephia Eagles are playing in a wild card match up against the\nbronckle this that and the other I guess that couldn't happen NFC versus AFC,\n\nwe turn that into Philadephia\nEagles\nplayoff\nwild card and all other terms\n\nand then we can map them in a hashmap of shorts to the documents\n\n\nplayoff: [event1, event2, event3]\nswift: [event5, event6, eventN]\n\nNow we have very quick lookup such that if somebody searches descriptoin for playoff then we can easily return\nall the events that mention playoffs, \nElasticSearch also has support for GeoSpatial queries that uses a combinatioin of quad tree and geohashing\n\nSo elastic search is good way to make these search queries as fast as possible.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How we will get available sheets for an event -> we will first check into database for all avaialbe\nsheets and then for sheets we will check in Redis if reserved we will filter out an sent back to client.\nwe need distributed lock due to booking service need to horizontally scaled so multiple booking\nservice will be there and all of them need this detail. \n\n\nInterview ask -> What happend if this lock goes down?\n\ni -> we would detect that this is down and we would immediately make it up that means if any of user\n    reserve that in last 10 minutes will lost their reservation and so in theory for a 10 minute window\nwe could have several users go to a payment page and try to book the same ticket because this is a postgres\nDB here and we still have the ACID properties on the write to available or booked meaning one write need\nto complete before another one could write\nwhoever end up submitting the purchase first is going to win and the other ones will get error and this is \na bad user experience. this is the conversation that we would have with the product team like is it okay\nif it is okay then that is the disaster when lock goes down.\nThen we will have small 10 minutes window where we are not going to lose our consistency guarantees but user\nare going to have bad user experience\n\n\nDeep Dive\nNon Functional Requirements ->\n\n1 Low Latency Search\n\nHow we handle low latency search -> we know our current solution is slow because we do a full table scan\nCommon solution for search problems like this is to introduce search optimize database and a very popular\none and one that recommended in our interviews is called elasticsearch.\n\nHow ElasticSearch work -> way that elasticsearch works is along with other things it builds an inverted index\n    to make searching documents by terms really quickly so we can imaging we have an event and the event has\nsome text for the name and description and may be other things that describe the event and what we are going\nto do is we are going to tokenize that string or those set of strings and create terms from them so we could\nimagine that the string might be the Philadephia Eagles are playing in a wild card match up against the\nbronckle this that and the other I guess that couldn't happen NFC versus AFC,\n\nwe turn that into Philadephia\nEagles\nplayoff\nwild card and all other terms\n\nand then we can map them in a hashmap of shorts to the documents\n\n\nplayoff: [event1, event2, event3]\nswift: [event5, event6, eventN]\n\nNow we have very quick lookup such that if somebody searches descriptoin for playoff then we can easily return\nall the events that mention playoffs, \nElasticSearch also has support for GeoSpatial queries that uses a combinatioin of quad tree and geohashing\n\nSo elastic search is good way to make these search queries as fast as possible.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "_ql7cnnn5Tro5js_pNzqx",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1412.354939052746,
      "y": 13017.09403581435,
      "width": 3167.99853515625,
      "height": 1170,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bIN",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 593450653,
      "version": 2338,
      "versionNonce": 813299871,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1770404286338,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "How do we get data into ElasticSearch and how do we make sure that data is consistent with what is in our\nprimary database?\n\nIts not best practice to use Elastic Search as our primary datastore. This is usually on the back of durability\nconcerns and it has no support for like complex transaction management\n\nActually we use a Elastic Search as a primary data store for our first startup and we learned the hard way that\nit didn't work out very well SO I know this from first experience.\n\nSo IN result we need someway to make sure if anything changes in our primary database that change gets propagated\nto elastic search and so there is couple of ways that we can do,\nthe simplest way is that we just handle this all in our application code so in this case anytime an event is added\nanytime an event is added we will write it to our postgress DB and we will also write it to elasticsearch, this \nputs some complex logic in our application code here. because we need to make sure what happen if DB write fail\nwhat happen with Elastic write so if Elastic fail then we need to retry this\n\n\nAnother popular solution is using whats called change data capture or CDC -> CDC is a process in for which changes\nto a primary datastore can be put onto a stream and then those change events can be consumed and something can\nbe done with them, So in this case if anytime something change that change event will be put on stream we can consume\nit and update elastic search with whatever that change was(41:20)\n\nElastic Search will have upper limit of write per second due to it need to change indexes accoridnlgy if we have a system there lot of updated to elastic search\nthen we need queue and some king of batching, But in our case we can say to interview events, venues, performers\nwill not change alot , may be admin adds 10, 100, 1000 a day whihc is absolutely fine. SO we dont need queue here\nwe can just update our elastic search on each change to our primary database.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "How do we get data into ElasticSearch and how do we make sure that data is consistent with what is in our\nprimary database?\n\nIts not best practice to use Elastic Search as our primary datastore. This is usually on the back of durability\nconcerns and it has no support for like complex transaction management\n\nActually we use a Elastic Search as a primary data store for our first startup and we learned the hard way that\nit didn't work out very well SO I know this from first experience.\n\nSo IN result we need someway to make sure if anything changes in our primary database that change gets propagated\nto elastic search and so there is couple of ways that we can do,\nthe simplest way is that we just handle this all in our application code so in this case anytime an event is added\nanytime an event is added we will write it to our postgress DB and we will also write it to elasticsearch, this \nputs some complex logic in our application code here. because we need to make sure what happen if DB write fail\nwhat happen with Elastic write so if Elastic fail then we need to retry this\n\n\nAnother popular solution is using whats called change data capture or CDC -> CDC is a process in for which changes\nto a primary datastore can be put onto a stream and then those change events can be consumed and something can\nbe done with them, So in this case if anytime something change that change event will be put on stream we can consume\nit and update elastic search with whatever that change was(41:20)\n\nElastic Search will have upper limit of write per second due to it need to change indexes accoridnlgy if we have a system there lot of updated to elastic search\nthen we need queue and some king of batching, But in our case we can say to interview events, venues, performers\nwill not change alot , may be admin adds 10, 100, 1000 a day whihc is absolutely fine. SO we dont need queue here\nwe can just update our elastic search on each change to our primary database.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "_VjND71aKoPjuA9UmEVQ2",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1415.8264497375148,
      "y": 14375.30337203412,
      "width": 2435.3994140625,
      "height": 540,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bIR",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 324980448,
      "version": 1163,
      "versionNonce": 649503953,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1770404286338,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Now interviewer can ask if someone is very famous like Taylor swift how can we make it fast as possible? -> answer is\ncaching we need to recognize in our system\nAWS opensearch uses node query caching it caches top 10K queries to that shard in a least recently used cache\n\nAnother thing we can use cache Redis or Memcache\n\n\nWE can use CDN in first place -> what CDN is going to do is that CDN can cach these api calls so it can cach the api\ncall and it results and usually when we cache an API endpoint in the CDN, its for a short period of time 30 sec or 1 minute\nor so. but that way if lot of people are searching for same exact search term then we can just return those results\nimmediately by hitting CDN which is geographically located close to them, its superfast but it would be very rare that\nother person are searching same search term. more query param less chance to CDN hit. so we just wasting space in CDN.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Now interviewer can ask if someone is very famous like Taylor swift how can we make it fast as possible? -> answer is\ncaching we need to recognize in our system\nAWS opensearch uses node query caching it caches top 10K queries to that shard in a least recently used cache\n\nAnother thing we can use cache Redis or Memcache\n\n\nWE can use CDN in first place -> what CDN is going to do is that CDN can cach these api calls so it can cach the api\ncall and it results and usually when we cache an API endpoint in the CDN, its for a short period of time 30 sec or 1 minute\nor so. but that way if lot of people are searching for same exact search term then we can just return those results\nimmediately by hitting CDN which is geographically located close to them, its superfast but it would be very rare that\nother person are searching same search term. more query param less chance to CDN hit. so we just wasting space in CDN.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "QUJGQ7SErO22n14nMWebW",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1398.5186367743995,
      "y": 15132.835250862108,
      "width": 2736.996826171875,
      "height": 5889.878299031453,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bIS",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1244101344,
      "version": 7555,
      "versionNonce": 1091538111,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1770404286338,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2 scalability to handle surges from popular events -> \n\nflow -> user comes to our website and they click on event they can see the event\ndetail about the event venue, performer and they are going to see a seatmap and \nthe seatmap is going to show them seats that are availalbe and that are alredy\nbooked, they can click on those that are available\nSo the way this work in our system right now\n\nthey would query our event crud service we would query to get our event venue and\nperformer and then we will query to get the ticket for that event with their available\nor booked status and then we  would need to cross reference that available or booked\nstatus with tickets that might be in our lock so anything that in our lock will be moved\nfrom available to reserved or just booked so that client know that it can't book\n\nthe issue with this is that we made that API call we loaded that up on client and now\nimmediately client sees an accurate representation but after 1 sec, 2sec, 5 sec , 5 minutes\n10 minutes its grown stale and now that can be clicking on seats that appear to be available\nbut they are not longer available and we are going to have to immediately give the user an\nerror thats a really bad experience so particularly for these popular events that would\nhappen alot like a lot of people are buying tickets so it could be sale really quickly so the\nfirst thing that we could do here is we could try to make that map realtime and this means\nanytime ticket becomes reseved or moved to booked we update the client to mark the seat in\nreal time as no longer available we could do this couple of ways \n\n1 We can use Long Polling -> Long polling is client opens up or send an http request and then\nthat request is kept open for usually like 30 sec to a minute or so for the server to be able\nto respond, this will happend in while loop we keep on long polling so the server can keep \nsending things back, and in our case keep the seats updated, it would be super cheap\nand easy to implement, required no additional infrastructure. Specially if the user is not\non this page for long time.\n\nWe can go with SSE or server sent event when server will have something it will send to \nclient no need to poll.\nin start client will initiate connection and then client or server can push info over the\nSSE connection\nSSE is unidirection only server to client, websockets are fully biderectional\nSSE we need here we only need our server to be able to tell our client that new seats\nhave been taken so thats something that we can do, we can say to our interviewer\nwe will setup persisting SSE conection between my API gateway and Event crud service\nand my client and every single time there is a change either of these on the status \navailable or booked or on my reserved, I am going to push that change to client, and a\nimplementation is little more complex it is out of scope from the interview.\n\n\nWhen the world cup come around the user experience is going to be that they go to that\npage and it immediately goes black they will see all these availalbe seat and then within\ncouple of miliseconds its just black due to everything got booked because 100K or million\npeople trying to fight for 10000 seats. , thats not great?\n\nthe solution is we need to introduce the choke point we basically need to protect our backend\nservices introduce a choke point, improve the user experience, whats reffered a virtual \nwaiting queue. so we would end up with, lets say I can make a room for this\n\nthis virtual waiting queue could be enabled only for very popular events, may be admin\nenabled there is some config and admin determines what events we should introduce a virtual\nwaiting queue for,\nIn high level we have a million people or so that all try to buy the ticket and instead of\nseeing the event detail page, they enter a waiting queue. and they get a message that\nsays thanks for your interest the queue we will let you know when you are out, the queue\ncould be redis here. We will probably have event driven logic such that once we have 100 seats\nbooked we let the first 100 people in, once we have 100 seats that are booked we let the\nnext 100 pull from the queue and we can notify user may be with SSE connection that we have\ncreated, prior they are ready to go and then user can be let in and that user can book.\n\nConsider this Back of invelope useless, withour purpose, math is good but recommendation is\nthat we only do calculations if the result of the caluculations will have a direct influence\non design and usually the right time to do that is either in our HLD or in Deep dives\nSo for example I do some math here and I won't because this video will go too long but I \ncould do some math to what the storage is here in this postgress DB to make determination\nas to whether we need to shard or not or it could fit into single postgress instance\nIf I came to the conclussion that we did need to shard then we could have a conversation\nabout what I need to shard on and may be thats eventId because thats what the majority of\nmy queries are in or if we are sharding and then distributing the shards geographically\nmay be we do over venue id if there is high corelation between people searching for events\nthat are in venues close to them then maybe that makes sense too.\n\n\nReads >> Writes\nwe can reduce read load on postgress specially due to event venue performer will never change\nor very infrequently change it makes them a great candidate to just cach them to hell\nso we can use Redis here, we can cache these event performer venue in redis, make sure if\nwe change these in database we will invalidate or update our cache as well. there doesn't need\nto be an eviction policy LIke LFU or LRU, probably we can fit them all in cache\n\nthen we only need to make a query  to get tickets because that one is dyanamic so we will not\ncache that one \n\nLast thing we can conclude with does this design satisfy all of my functional requirements\n& non functional requirements if we can say yes to both then we can feel confident",
      "fontSize": 52.9427262834288,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2 scalability to handle surges from popular events -> \n\nflow -> user comes to our website and they click on event they can see the event\ndetail about the event venue, performer and they are going to see a seatmap and \nthe seatmap is going to show them seats that are availalbe and that are alredy\nbooked, they can click on those that are available\nSo the way this work in our system right now\n\nthey would query our event crud service we would query to get our event venue and\nperformer and then we will query to get the ticket for that event with their available\nor booked status and then we  would need to cross reference that available or booked\nstatus with tickets that might be in our lock so anything that in our lock will be moved\nfrom available to reserved or just booked so that client know that it can't book\n\nthe issue with this is that we made that API call we loaded that up on client and now\nimmediately client sees an accurate representation but after 1 sec, 2sec, 5 sec , 5 minutes\n10 minutes its grown stale and now that can be clicking on seats that appear to be available\nbut they are not longer available and we are going to have to immediately give the user an\nerror thats a really bad experience so particularly for these popular events that would\nhappen alot like a lot of people are buying tickets so it could be sale really quickly so the\nfirst thing that we could do here is we could try to make that map realtime and this means\nanytime ticket becomes reseved or moved to booked we update the client to mark the seat in\nreal time as no longer available we could do this couple of ways \n\n1 We can use Long Polling -> Long polling is client opens up or send an http request and then\nthat request is kept open for usually like 30 sec to a minute or so for the server to be able\nto respond, this will happend in while loop we keep on long polling so the server can keep \nsending things back, and in our case keep the seats updated, it would be super cheap\nand easy to implement, required no additional infrastructure. Specially if the user is not\non this page for long time.\n\nWe can go with SSE or server sent event when server will have something it will send to \nclient no need to poll.\nin start client will initiate connection and then client or server can push info over the\nSSE connection\nSSE is unidirection only server to client, websockets are fully biderectional\nSSE we need here we only need our server to be able to tell our client that new seats\nhave been taken so thats something that we can do, we can say to our interviewer\nwe will setup persisting SSE conection between my API gateway and Event crud service\nand my client and every single time there is a change either of these on the status \navailable or booked or on my reserved, I am going to push that change to client, and a\nimplementation is little more complex it is out of scope from the interview.\n\n\nWhen the world cup come around the user experience is going to be that they go to that\npage and it immediately goes black they will see all these availalbe seat and then within\ncouple of miliseconds its just black due to everything got booked because 100K or million\npeople trying to fight for 10000 seats. , thats not great?\n\nthe solution is we need to introduce the choke point we basically need to protect our backend\nservices introduce a choke point, improve the user experience, whats reffered a virtual \nwaiting queue. so we would end up with, lets say I can make a room for this\n\nthis virtual waiting queue could be enabled only for very popular events, may be admin\nenabled there is some config and admin determines what events we should introduce a virtual\nwaiting queue for,\nIn high level we have a million people or so that all try to buy the ticket and instead of\nseeing the event detail page, they enter a waiting queue. and they get a message that\nsays thanks for your interest the queue we will let you know when you are out, the queue\ncould be redis here. We will probably have event driven logic such that once we have 100 seats\nbooked we let the first 100 people in, once we have 100 seats that are booked we let the\nnext 100 pull from the queue and we can notify user may be with SSE connection that we have\ncreated, prior they are ready to go and then user can be let in and that user can book.\n\nConsider this Back of invelope useless, withour purpose, math is good but recommendation is\nthat we only do calculations if the result of the caluculations will have a direct influence\non design and usually the right time to do that is either in our HLD or in Deep dives\nSo for example I do some math here and I won't because this video will go too long but I \ncould do some math to what the storage is here in this postgress DB to make determination\nas to whether we need to shard or not or it could fit into single postgress instance\nIf I came to the conclussion that we did need to shard then we could have a conversation\nabout what I need to shard on and may be thats eventId because thats what the majority of\nmy queries are in or if we are sharding and then distributing the shards geographically\nmay be we do over venue id if there is high corelation between people searching for events\nthat are in venues close to them then maybe that makes sense too.\n\n\nReads >> Writes\nwe can reduce read load on postgress specially due to event venue performer will never change\nor very infrequently change it makes them a great candidate to just cach them to hell\nso we can use Redis here, we can cache these event performer venue in redis, make sure if\nwe change these in database we will invalidate or update our cache as well. there doesn't need\nto be an eviction policy LIke LFU or LRU, probably we can fit them all in cache\n\nthen we only need to make a query  to get tickets because that one is dyanamic so we will not\ncache that one \n\nLast thing we can conclude with does this design satisfy all of my functional requirements\n& non functional requirements if we can say yes to both then we can feel confident",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
